			<td><div id="main_content">
			<div id="bread_crumbs"><a class='crumb' href='/cms/'>Home</a> &gt; OSG Newsletter June 2011<br /><br /></div>
<p />
<table cellPadding="0" cellSpacing="10" border="0" bgColor="#ffffcc" width="100%"><tbody><tr bgColor="#ffffcc" borderColor="#999999"><td vAlign="middle" width="146"><p><a href="http://www.opensciencegrid.org/"><img longDesc="https//www.opensciencegrid.org/images/osg_logo.gif" border="0" src="/images/osg-logo.gif" alt="OSG Logo" align="middle" height="82" width="144" /></a></p><br /></td><td vAlign="top" align="left" width="390"><h1>OSG Newsletter, June 2011</h1></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p><table cellPadding="0" cellSpacing="10" border="0" bgColor="#fdebcf" style="width: 697px; height: 2759px" height="2759" width="697"><tbody><tr><td vAlign="top" align="left" height="1740" width="50%"><p><strong>Reader Survey - Win Amazon gift card</strong> </p><p>The Open Science Grid consists of a diverse community, and so is the readership of this newsletter. We want to learn more about you and what you want from this newsletter. That&#39;s why we&#39;ve created a short reader survey that we hope you will fill out. </p><p>As an added incentive, we&#39;ll be conducting a draw from among our participants. The winner will receive a $25 gift card for Amazon.com. </p><p>Go to the <a target="_blank" href="https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/OSGNewsletterReaderSurvey"><font color="#0066cc">survey now</font></a>.</p><hr /><strong>Introducing ALICE</strong> <p>Until recently, the <a target="_blank" href="http://aliceinfo.cern.ch/"><font color="#0066cc">ALICE </font></a>experiment (based at the Large Hadron Collider) did not have any computing resources on OSG, or indeed in the United States. But during 2010, the ALICE USA collaboration installed significant compute and storage resources (about 1200 CPU-cores and one petabyte of disk space) for ALICE at two new Tier 2 centers located at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory. </p><p>ALICE relies on a mature grid framework known as <span class="twikiNewLink">AliEn<a href="/bin/edit/Management/AliEn?topicparent=Management.Jun2011Newsletter" rel="nofollow" title="AliEn (this topic does not yet exist; you can create it)">?</a></span> to provide computing resources in a production environment for the simulation, reconstruction and analysis of physics data. Developed by the ALICE Collaboration, <span class="twikiNewLink">AliEn<a href="/bin/edit/Management/AliEn?topicparent=Management.Jun2011Newsletter" rel="nofollow" title="AliEn (this topic does not yet exist; you can create it)">?</a></span> is based on the pilot job submission model. It has been operational for many years and is currently deployed at nearly 90 ALICE and WLCG facilities worldwide. </p><p>The new LBNL site is part of the NERSC/PDSF facility; it is the OSG site where the <span class="twikiNewLink">AliEn<a href="/bin/edit/Management/AliEn?topicparent=Management.Jun2011Newsletter" rel="nofollow" title="AliEn (this topic does not yet exist; you can create it)">?</a></span>-OSG interface was initially developed and tested. The LLNL facility is a new resource within Livermore Computing that has recently been integrated with OSG for the purposes of providing accounting reports for ALICE to WLCG and managing disposition of spare cycles to other DOE Nuclear Physics-sponsored projects. ALICE USA plans to steadily increase the capacity of ALICE-OSG resources over the next few years. </p><p>~ Jeff Porter </p><hr /><strong></strong><strong>From the Executive Director</strong> <p>The past month has brought another peak in usage of resources available through the OSG (see attached plot). Existing non-physics users are looking for additional resources and we are starting to understand how to more quickly determine potential bottlenecks and communicate and prioritize requests in a more timely manner. </p><p>In May Rick Snider took over from Kent Blackburn as one of the Council Co-Chairs. Paul Avery will continue to work with Rick in coordinating the OSG Council, which is the governing body of the Consortium. </p><p>We greatly appreciate the commitments and efforts that Kent has brought to the Consortium over the past five plus years -- 3 as Council Co-Chair -- and the help he has given us in moving the value and effectiveness of the organization forward. In keeping with tradition I am sending him a framed certificate expressing our appreciation and best wishes </p><p>We are once again in the annual planning cycle for the program of work for FY12. We are extending our attention to requirements gathering, including dedicated effort in the software area for software requirements. Robert Gardner, as a representative of the project management team, will be working on assessments of OSG objectives and accomplishments moving forward. </p><p>~ Ruth Pordes Executive Director </p><hr /><strong>CMS &amp; ATLAS Thumbnails </strong><table border="1" width="200"><tbody><tr><td><a target="_blank" href="/images/ATLAS_may11.png"><img longDesc="https://www.opensciencegrid.org/images/ATLAS_mar11.png" src="/images/CMS_may11.png" alt="CMS Thumbnails" height="140" width="180" /></a></td><td><a target="_blank" href="/images/ATLAS_may11.png"><img longDesc="https://www.opensciencegrid.org/images/ATLAS_mar11.png" src="/images/ATLAS_may11.png" alt="ATLAS Thumbnails" height="139" width="180" /></a></td></tr></tbody></table><hr /><p><strong>OSG Documents updated in the last 30 days</strong> </p><table cellPadding="0" border="0"><tbody><tr><td><p align="center">OSG-doc-#</p></td><td><p align="center">Title</p></td><td><p align="center">Author(s)</p></td><td><p align="center">Topic(s)</p></td><td><p align="center">Last Updated</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1057" title="OSG-doc-1057-v1"><font color="#0066cc">1057-v1</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1057" title="OSG-doc-1057-v1"><font color="#0066cc">OSG Strategic Planning and Assessment</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?authorid=110" title="University of Chicago"><font color="#0066cc">Rob Gardner</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=77" title="Communications:Strategic Plans"><font color="#0066cc">Strategic Plans</font></a><br /><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=76" title="Activities:Metrics"><font color="#0066cc">Metrics</font></a></p></td><td><p>23 Jun 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1056" title="OSG-doc-1056-v1"><font color="#0066cc">1056-v1</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1056" title="OSG-doc-1056-v1"><font color="#0066cc">ExTENCI Project Annual Report 2010-2011, June 2011</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?authorid=159" title="University of Florida"><font color="#0066cc">Paul Avery</font></a> et al.</p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=62" title="Governance:Reports"><font color="#0066cc">Reports</font></a></p></td><td><p>22 Jun 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1055" title="OSG-doc-1055-v1"><font color="#0066cc">1055-v1</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1055" title="OSG-doc-1055-v1"><font color="#0066cc">US LHC Tier2 Activity for May 2011</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?authorid=381" title="University of Nebraska"><font color="#0066cc">Adam Caprez</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=76" title="Activities:Metrics"><font color="#0066cc">Metrics</font></a></p></td><td><p>10 Jun 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=998" title="OSG-doc-998-v4"><font color="#0066cc">998-v4</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=998" title="OSG-doc-998-v4"><font color="#0066cc">Year5 OSG Workplan Source Data</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?authorid=323" title="Open Science Grid"><font color="#0066cc">OSG Executive Board</font></a> et al.</p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=85" title="Governance:Work Plans:Year Five Workplans"><font color="#0066cc">Year Five Workplans</font></a></p></td><td><p>02 Jun 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1054" title="OSG-doc-1054-v0"><font color="#0066cc">1054-v0</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1054" title="OSG-doc-1054-v0"><font color="#0066cc">OSG Annual Report to NSF (June 2011)</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?authorid=159" title="University of Florida"><font color="#0066cc">Paul Avery</font></a> et al.</p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=4" title="Governance"><font color="#0066cc">Governance</font></a><br /><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=62" title="Governance:Reports"><font color="#0066cc">Reports</font></a></p></td><td><p>31 May 2011</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1011" title="OSG-doc-1011-v1"><font color="#0066cc">1011-v1</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1011" title="OSG-doc-1011-v1"><font color="#0066cc">OSG Annual Report to DOE (December 2010)</font></a></p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?authorid=159" title="University of Florida"><font color="#0066cc">Paul Avery</font></a> et al.</p></td><td><p><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=4" title="Governance"><font color="#0066cc">Governance</font></a><br /><a href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ListBy?topicid=62" title="Governance:Reports"><font color="#0066cc">Reports</font></a></p></td><td><p>31 May 2011</p></td></tr></tbody></table></td><td width="50%"><p><strong>CMS Production Report</strong></p><p>Once again, the <a target="_blank" href="http://lhc.web.cern.ch/lhc/"><font color="#0066cc">LHC</font></a> has done quite well and exceeded expectations. In just the last month, we reached an inverse femtobarn delivered to the detector, which was our nominal goal for the entire year. We are making wider use of our Data Popularity Service, which measures which <a target="_blank" href="http://cms.web.cern.ch/cms/index.html"><font color="#0066cc">CMS</font></a> datasets are the most accessed. Our heavy ion dataset ranked as the second most popular, and the corresponding results were well-received at Quark Matter 2011. </p><p>~ Burt Holzman </p><hr /><strong>ATLAS Report</strong> <p>Since LHC operations resumed in March the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.atlas.ch/"><font color="#0066cc">ATLAS</font></a> collaboration has recorded about 570 million collision events with their detector. The cumulative data volume of RAW and derived data for this year&rsquo;s run amounts to 2.3 PB so far. Only a fraction of the total is replicated to sites in the U.S., i.e. 180 TB of RAW, 200 TB of AOD (Analysis Object Data), 200 TB of dESD (derived Event Summary Data) and some 50 TB of other compact datasets meaningful to analysis. </p><p>With ATLAS heavily building on replication-on-demand rather than programmatic data pre-placement, up to twenty additional replicas of popular datasets were dynamically created at Tier-1 and Tier-2 sites worldwide. The result was that the typical job wait time of user analysis jobs in batch queues was reduced to 1-2 hours. </p><p>During the past four weeks Panda production services completed 9.6 million analysis, managed group, MC production, validation and reprocessing jobs at 96% efficiency. Out of that total, 23% -- or 2.2 million jobs -- ran on OSG resources provided by sites in the U.S. that support the ATLAS VO. </p><p>~ Michael Ernst</p><hr /><p><strong>ExTENCI Annual Report</strong></p><div id="sites-canvas-main"><div id="sites-canvas-main-content"><table xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" cellSpacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><div dir="ltr">OSG is participating in a joint project with Teragrid to Extend Science Through Enhanced National Cyberinfrastructure (<a target="_blank" href="https://sites.google.com/site/extenci/"><font color="#0066cc">ExTENCI)</font></a>. The goal is to develop and provide production quality enhancements to the national cyberinfrastructure that will enable specific science applications to more easily use both OSG and TG, or make applications previously available to only one cyberinfrastructure available to both. This is a two-year project funded by the National Science Foundation&#39;s Mathematical and Physical Sciences directorate and Office of Cyberinfrastructure. <br /><br />ExTENCI is a combination of four technology components, each run as a separate project with one or more science projects targeted as the first user. The components and respective sciences are: Workflow &amp; Client Tools &ndash; Southern California Earthquake Center and protein modeling; Distributed File System &ndash; CMS/ATLAS; Virtual Machines &ndash; STAR and CMS; and Job Submission Paradigms &ndash; Cactus Applications (<span class="twikiNewLink">EnKF<a href="/bin/edit/Management/EnKF?topicparent=Management.Jun2011Newsletter" rel="nofollow" title="EnKF (this topic does not yet exist; you can create it)">?</a></span> and Coastal Modeling). <br /><br />Another important benefit of <a href="/bin/view/Management/ExTENCI" class="twikiLink">ExTENCI</a> has been to provide an opportunity for cooperation and joint activity between OSG and TG. Each of the projects has fostered sharing of information, joint problem solving, and combined teams to better serve users across both environments, and thus pave the way for OSG to become a Service Provider in XSEDE. <br /><br />After 10 months, significant progress has been made by each of the projects:<br /><ul><li>Workflow &amp; Client Tools has been working in two main areas -- earthquake hazard prediction (from the SCEC project) and protein structure analysis. We have demonstrated a method using the Swift workflow engine that can obtain large (~2000) numbers of nodes from OSG Engage Virtual Organization (VO) sites, built and generalized a framework that allows this to be done, and demonstrated it with another application. This has allowed running instances of straightforward applications (protein and glass modeling) on OSG as well as on TG. The SCEC application has been run on both OSG and TG. But in the case of the SCEC application, the intense data transfer needs required reformulation of the application to limit data transfers. The result was that we were able to do 92% of the computing while moving only 32% of the data; the remaining computations remain on TG. Current work is on optimizing methods for determining how to divide the work between OSG and TG. </li><li>Distributed File System has set up the hardware at three sites, installed the Kerberos security infrastructure, added Kerberos to the Lustre/WAN file system, and installed the Lustre server software at two sites (as planned) and Lustre client software at two sites. Now we are doing performance testing between sites. Some performance issues have been identified and tests of possible solutions are in progress. Science application testing was started but is on hold until the performance issues are resolved. </li><li>Virtual Machines has deployed hypervisors on a large scale at Clemson (OSG) and Purdue (TG) and verified that the STAR VM can be run on OSG and TG and that the CMS VM runs on TG. We have tested and documented Condor-G&rsquo;s support of cloud services, created a report on tools used to author VMs and manage libraries of such machines, and have cataloged VM distribution mechanisms in preparation for developing tools to assist users in these areas. </li><li>Job Submission Paradigms has completed the overall design and has implemented the SAGA Condor-G adapter that is now being tested by sending jobs to both TG and OSG. Verification of operation and performance of a science application is awaiting completion of this testing. </li></ul><p><br />More information can be found in the<a target="_blank" href="https://osg-docdb.opensciencegrid.org:440/cgi-bin/ShowDocument?docid=1056%20"><font color="#0066cc"> <a href="/bin/view/Management/ExTENCI" class="twikiLink">ExTENCI</a> Annual Report</font></a>.</p><p>~ Jim Weichel</p><hr /></div></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p></div></div></td></tr><tr></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>
<p />
